Melton Borough Council used a crisis—the destruction of its old offices by fire—to regenerate its area and secure financial stability, but now faces severe funding challenges due to central government cuts. Leicestershire, historically underfunded, struggles with a significant budget gap despite receiving some transitional funding, while Labour councils argue the funding system is unfairly political. Council leaders, including Byron Rhodes, are advocating for a fairer funding formula as the government shifts to a new system based on business rates by 2020.
Pep Guardiola admitted his first Premier League season with Manchester City has not met expectations, promising improvement in the future. City’s defeat to Chelsea has likely ended their title hopes, leaving Champions League qualification as their main target. Guardiola also addressed a post-match staff altercation, emphasizing respect and sportsmanship.
The Welsh government has withdrawn plans for 10 new marine conservation zones after receiving 7,000 consultation responses with strongly held, divergent views. Instead, they will review the effectiveness of the existing 125 marine protected areas. The Marine Conservation Society criticized the move as an "embarrassing U-turn," calling for stronger sea protection.
Boris Johnson, the charismatic Mayor of London and prominent Conservative politician, announced his support for the UK's campaign to leave the European Union, significantly impacting the Brexit debate and financial markets. Known for his eccentric persona and controversial remarks, Johnson's decision was described as heartfelt and potentially risky for his political career. Despite controversies, his popularity endures, and his stance may influence undecided voters and his future leadership prospects.
A lorry collided with a broken-down rail replacement bus carrying 50 passengers on the A34 in Oxfordshire, injuring three people, one seriously but not life-threateningly. The incident caused significant traffic delays and required the closure of the southbound carriageway for investigations and vehicle recovery. First Great Western is supporting affected passengers, while police continue to investigate the crash.
Ricky Burns made history by becoming the first Scot to win world boxing titles in three weight classes after defeating Michele Di Rocco for the WBA World Super-Lightweight title in Glasgow. Despite previous setbacks and being written off, Burns delivered a dominant performance and remained humble in victory. His achievement places him among Scotland's boxing greats, and he now looks forward to potential high-profile fights.
A survey of senior officials reveals that adult social care in England faces severe staff shortages and declining service quality due to £4.6bn in funding cuts since 2010 and a further £1.1bn shortfall this year. Councils and charities warn that continued underfunding is excluding vulnerable people from essential support. The government claims increased investment and integration with the NHS will improve care, but local leaders argue this is insufficient.
Terminally ill actor and disability campaigner Lord Brian Rix, 92, has called for a change in the law to allow assisted dying, reversing his previous opposition due to his own suffering. He wrote to the House of Lords, describing his constant discomfort and desire for a peaceful, legal death. Rix emphasized that many others in similar situations would benefit from legal euthanasia, and his family fully supports his decision.
Police in Northern Ireland uncovered a significant cache of weapons, including rockets and mines, in Capanagh Forest near Larne, likely linked to dissident republicans. The discovery, made by two members of the public, is believed to have prevented potential attacks and saved lives. Authorities are investigating possible connections to a similar arms find nearby in March.
Kenya’s election result counting has slowed due to electronic system failures, forcing officials to deliver paper tallies to Nairobi, causing public anxiety and business disruptions. Uhuru Kenyatta leads early results, but rival Raila Odinga’s supporters expect gains as more votes are counted. Disputes over spoiled ballots and potential legal challenges could lead to a runoff if no candidate secures the required majority.
Formula 1 driver Maria de Villota lost her right eye after suffering serious head and facial injuries in a crash during her first test with the Marussia team at Duxford airfield. The accident occurred when her car accelerated into a support truck, prompting a lengthy operation and ongoing investigation. The racing community has expressed shock and support, while de Villota remains in critical but stable condition.
The US Supreme Court, in a 6-3 decision, upheld tax subsidies under President Obama's Affordable Care Act, preserving health insurance for millions of low-income Americans. The ruling secures Obamacare as a central part of Obama's legacy, despite ongoing Republican opposition. Had the decision gone the other way, an estimated 8.7 million people risked losing affordable healthcare coverage.
A new Russian law requires bloggers with over 3,000 daily readers to register with authorities and comply with media regulations, while social networks must store user data on Russian servers for government access. Critics, including human rights groups, view the law as a crackdown on internet freedom and free expression. Many bloggers are seeking ways to evade the restrictions, as enforcement remains challenging due to foreign-based servers.
Western Sahara has welcomed Morocco’s readmission to the African Union after 32 years, viewing it as an opportunity for dialogue and resolution. Despite Morocco’s control over most of Western Sahara, the territory is still considered Africa’s last colony by some, including the UN, and a promised referendum on independence remains unfulfilled. The AU hopes Morocco’s return will facilitate progress, though divisions persist among member states regarding Western Sahara’s status.
After a lightning storm temporarily halted Glastonbury Festival, Arcade Fire revived the crowd with an energetic, confetti-filled headline set featuring dancers and inclusive messages. Other acts, including Rudimental and Blondie, also performed despite weather disruptions, while Lily Allen and Chvrches contributed to the festival’s diverse atmosphere. The event continued with high spirits, drawing both music fans and celebrities.
Mead, once a historic drink associated with medieval Europe, is experiencing a revival in the US, with the number of commercial meaderies growing from about 40 to 250 in the past decade. Modern meaderies like Maine Mead Works are producing more refined and diverse meads, moving beyond the traditional sweet varieties. Despite increased interest, the industry faces challenges in public awareness and overcoming outdated perceptions, but enthusiasts see significant growth potential.
Lady Gaga is set to headline the Super Bowl halftime show, promising a career-spanning performance on one of the world's biggest stages. The article highlights memorable past halftime moments, from Michael Jackson's dramatic entrance to Beyonce's political statement and Janet Jackson's infamous "wardrobe malfunction." These iconic performances have shaped the halftime show's evolution into a major cultural event.
President Obama criticized David Cameron for becoming "distracted" after the 2011 Libya intervention, which he said left the country in chaos despite initial military success. Obama also expressed frustration with European allies for not investing enough in post-conflict efforts and defense spending. Downing Street defended the intervention as necessary to protect civilians, emphasizing that Libya's future must be led by its own people.
Dawn Purvis is stepping down as programme director of Northern Ireland's Marie Stopes clinic, the region's first private provider of early medical abortions, after leading it since its 2012 launch. She will remain involved as a member of the clinic's advisory board. Purvis emphasized the clinic's progress and her role in changing perceptions about abortion in Northern Ireland.
St Johnstone defeated ten-man Inverness Caledonian Thistle 3-0, leaving Inverness four points adrift at the bottom of the Scottish Premiership. Inverness struggled to threaten, had Larnell Cole sent off, and saw captain Gary Warren red-carded after the match. St Johnstone capitalized on their advantage with goals from Steven MacLean, Liam Craig, and Graham Cummins, strengthening their position in fourth place.
Deputy First Minister John Swinney will address the Scottish Parliament regarding the Named Person scheme, following a Supreme Court ruling that its information-sharing proposals breached privacy rights. The court found the scheme's aim to support children's wellbeing legitimate but required changes to information-sharing provisions. The Scottish government remains committed to the scheme and will update parliament on next steps after consulting stakeholders.
Neil Lennon, former Celtic and Bolton manager, has taken charge at Hibernian, viewing the Championship role as an opportunity to rebuild his career and deliver success. Hibs, with a strong squad and top-flight infrastructure, seek promotion after missing out last season despite winning the Scottish Cup. Lennon's appointment is mutually beneficial, offering stability and ambition for both manager and club.
UK manufacturing activity contracted in April for the first time in three years, with the Markit/CIPS PMI falling to 49.2, signaling declining output. Firms cited weak domestic and overseas demand, oil and gas sector struggles, and EU referendum uncertainty as key factors. The downturn has led to job losses and heightened concerns about the sector's impact on overall economic growth.
The PSNI has launched a murder inquiry after prison officer Adrian Ismay died from injuries sustained in a dissident republican bomb attack in Belfast. The new IRA claimed responsibility, targeting Ismay for training officers at Maghaberry Prison. Prison officials condemned the celebratory behavior of some inmates following his death, while police continue to seek information on vehicles linked to the attack.
Prime Minister David Cameron is prioritizing the fight against global corruption by hosting the first international anti-corruption summit in London, bringing together world leaders, businesses, and organizations. The summit aims to expose, punish, and drive out corruption, with leaders pledging concrete action. Campaigners urge ambitious reforms, including a crackdown on tax havens, to ensure lasting impact.
An investigation found that some GP practices in England are being offered financial incentives by NHS groups to reduce hospital referrals, including for specialist consultations and scans. Critics, including the British Medical Association, argue these schemes risk undermining patient trust and could deter necessary care. NHS officials defend the incentives as promoting best practices and cost savings, not denying essential treatment.
A Chinese woman's claim that her husband divorced her due to her "fat face," prompting her to undergo multiple plastic surgeries, sparked heated debate on social media. The story, though unverified and lacking the husband's perspective, highlighted societal pressures and the booming cosmetic surgery industry in China. Online reactions ranged from criticism of both the husband and wife to skepticism about the lawsuit and compensation.
Welwyn Garden City’s Coronation Fountain, previously turned off due to a hosepipe ban, will be refilled with water purchased from a local landscaping company for Jubilee and Olympic celebrations. The water, sourced from a natural lake and not suitable for drinking, complies with ban regulations. The council chose this sustainable solution over requesting a special dispensation from the water company.
Harper Lee’s "To Kill a Mockingbird" remains her only novel, as she chose not to write another due to the loss of privacy and feeling she had already said what she wanted. Initially controversial in her hometown for its depiction of racism, the book later became a source of civic pride. Lee, who avoids publicity, is protected by her community and remembered for her powerful contribution to American literature.
Adam Peaty defended his 50m breaststroke title at the World Aquatics Championships, completing a double-double after also retaining his 100m title, narrowly missing his own world record. Other notable performances included Georgia Davies setting a British record in the 50m backstroke and Chad le Clos winning the 200m butterfly. The event also saw a surprise as Katie Ledecky was defeated by Federica Pellegrini in the 200m freestyle final.
Chris and Sue Moores, whose son Wayne was killed by a drunk driver, argue that proposed life sentences for causing death by careless driving under the influence do not go far enough. They believe such offences should be prosecuted as manslaughter, not just as careless driving. The Ministry of Justice is currently consulting on increasing the maximum sentence from 14 years to life.
Nine British nationals, including four children, were detained in Turkey for allegedly attempting to cross into Syria illegally near the Hatay province border. Their intended destination within Syria remains unclear, but authorities suspect possible links to militant groups. The incident highlights increased Turkish efforts to prevent foreign fighters from entering Syria and ongoing cooperation with Western nations.
A congregation in North Yorkshire has spent £10,000 building heated bat lofts to encourage bats to leave St Hilda's Church, where they have been roosting and causing significant mess and odor. Despite these efforts, the bats remain, as they are protected by law and cannot be disturbed. Authorities insist the bats can only be moved once suitable alternative roosts are confirmed.
Baltimore Mayor Stephanie Rawlings-Blake fired Police Commissioner Anthony Batts, citing his leadership as a distraction amid a surge in violent crime following Freddie Gray's death in police custody. Deputy Kevin Davis was appointed interim chief as the city faces increased homicides and ongoing investigations into police conduct. The police union criticized Batts' handling of recent riots, but the mayor denied their report influenced her decision.
Asghar Buksh admitted to killing his estranged wife, Nasreen Buksh, while she slept in their Glasgow home, claiming diminished responsibility due to acute stress disorder. The court heard their marriage had deteriorated, and Buksh had no memory of the incident, which psychiatrists confirmed was linked to his mental state. Sentencing is scheduled for 27 June.
UKIP's national executive committee rejected a call to deselect Welsh assembly member Michelle Brown, citing improper process after activists accused her of being abrasive and discourteous. The party dismissed the complaint as coming from a small, disgruntled group. Meanwhile, the NEC approved 11 candidates, including controversial figures, to run for party leadership.
The trial of members of the banned Church of the Almighty God cult began in Yantai, China, after they beat a woman to death in a McDonald's for refusing to give her phone number. The murder, captured on video, sparked public outrage and led to a crackdown with hundreds of cult members detained. The cult, which believes God has returned as a Chinese woman, is known for its hostility toward the Chinese government.
England and Pakistan played to a dramatic draw in the first Test in Abu Dhabi, with England falling 25 runs short of victory due to bad light after a late surge led by Adil Rashid's five wickets. England's strong performance, highlighted by Alastair Cook's record 263 and improved bowling, gave them confidence for the next Test. Missed chances and earlier mistakes ultimately cost England a win, but the team showed significant progress compared to previous overseas tours.
Archaeologists have discovered a 6,000-year-old "eco-home" at Blick Mead near Stonehenge, built in a tree hollow and used over 90 years from 4336 BC. The shelter featured a tree stump wall, animal skin or thatch coverings, and heated stones for warmth. Experts warn that a proposed A303 road tunnel could damage this significant archaeological site and its valuable organic remains.
Egyptian internet activists were instrumental in initiating and publicizing the pro-democracy protests, using social media to mobilize and connect diverse groups. As the movement grew, online activism evolved to support real-life organization and community-building in Tahrir Square, even when internet access was restricted. Activists emphasize that while technology facilitated the revolution, its true strength lies in the people and their offline solidarity.
Edinburgh's winter festivals attracted nearly one million visitors and generated over £241 million for the city. The Christmas events drew about 890,000 people, contributing £199.5 million, while Hogmanay celebrations brought in over 150,000 visitors and £41.8 million. Organisers emphasized that this revenue benefits local businesses across various sectors.
The future of struggling department store BHS is expected to be decided soon, with administrators likely to announce whether a rescue deal can be reached. Greg Tufnell, backed by Portuguese investors, is the leading bidder after other contenders faded, but liquidation remains possible if no agreement is made. Ongoing stock sell-offs and loss-making stores complicate the rescue, potentially leading to the business being broken up and sold off.
A North Wales firm proposes using DNA from dog mess to identify owners who fail to clean up after their pets, by matching samples to a database created from registered dogs’ mouth swabs. Up to 15 UK councils are interested in adopting the US-based PooPrints service. The initiative aims to create cleaner public spaces and could be enforced under the Antisocial Behaviour and Policing Act 2014.
Sport funding in Scotland will be cut by 20% over three years due to reduced government spending and lower National Lottery ticket sales, prompting concerns about impacts on elite athletes and potential job losses. The national agency, sportscotland, has not yet determined where the cuts will fall. Despite the reductions, the government emphasizes continued investment in sport and physical activity to address health inequalities.
Welsh political parties are preparing for another election next year, with the Conservatives buoyed by recent gains and planning to contest more constituencies, especially by focusing on NHS issues. Welsh Labour faces internal challenges and voter losses to UKIP, while Plaid Cymru and the Liberal Democrats are reassessing strategies after disappointing results. Each party is analyzing its performance and adjusting tactics to strengthen its position ahead of the upcoming vote.
Research by the Fostering Network reveals that nearly half of fostered teenagers in Scotland have lived with at least three different families, highlighting a lack of stability in the care system. The group warns that 750 more foster carers are urgently needed, especially for teenagers, siblings, and disabled children. Instability negatively affects children's wellbeing and education, prompting calls for more people to become foster carers and provide stable homes.
Historical Chinese records reveal that Hainan gibbons, now reduced to just 26–28 individuals in isolated forests, were once widespread across half of China. Their sharp decline began about 150 years ago, coinciding with rapid population growth and deforestation. Understanding this timeline helps scientists develop better conservation strategies for the critically endangered species.
All four schools managed by the Telford Co-operative Multi-Academy Trust have been placed in special measures within a week, following Ofsted inspections that rated them inadequate in all areas. Inspectors criticized weak teaching, poor leadership, and a lack of support from the trust, leading to declining pupil achievement. While some recent improvement initiatives were noted, all schools are now considering alternative sponsors.
Over a million EU citizens have signed a petition opposing trade talks with the US (TTIP) and the ratification of a similar EU-Canada deal, citing threats to democracy and public services like the NHS. The petition particularly criticizes investor-state dispute settlement tribunals, which campaigners argue could let foreign companies sue governments over policy changes. Although the European Commission defends these provisions, it faces legal challenges after rejecting the petition as a formal European Citizens' Initiative.
Diageo, through its investment arm Distill Ventures, has invested in Melbourne-based Starward Whisky to expand into new export markets. This follows a recent investment in Denmark's Stauning Whisky, reflecting Diageo's strategy to support early-stage spirits brands. The investment aims to boost Starward's production and innovation as Australian whisky gains global recognition.
Ruskin College in Oxford is cutting several degree programs, including BA English Studies and MA Women's Studies, due to low student numbers, prompting concerns it is moving away from its mission to serve working-class and mature students. Students and alumni have launched petitions to save the courses, emphasizing the college's tradition of inclusivity. The principal insists the college will continue focusing on adult education, despite the changes.
The inquest into the 1976 Kingsmill massacre, where 10 Protestant workers were killed by the IRA, has been delayed due to a shortage of coroners in Northern Ireland. Senior coroner John Leckey’s retirement leaves only one coroner, causing widespread delays for Troubles-related inquests. Victims’ families and politicians are urging the justice department to provide more resources and prioritize these cases.
Rare Leonardo da Vinci drawings from the Queen's royal collection are on display at Nottingham Castle Museum until 9 October. The exhibition features portraits, anatomical sketches, botanical studies, and technical drawings. Experts regard da Vinci's nearly 600 drawings in the Royal Collection as exceptionally rich and technically brilliant.
